  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding the nature of customers' business activities\n\n2. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining records of financial activities\n- Identifying unusual patterns or high-risk transactions\n\n3. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) regulations\n- Implementing comprehensive AML programs\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n\n5. Employee Training\n- Educating staff about money laundering risks\n- Teaching identification and reporting procedures\n- Ensuring ongoing compliance awareness\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Evaluating potential money laundering vulnerabilities\n- Implementing risk-based compliance strategies\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.",
